ow]]\n|1\n|-\n|10 January\n|\"[[Blinding Lights]]\"\n|[[The Weeknd]]\n|1\n|-\n|17 January\n|\"Mitten av September\"\n|[[Hov1]]\n|1\n|-\n|24 January\n|\"Svag\"\n|[[Victor Leksell]]\n|7\n|-\n|13 March\n|\"[[Move (The Mamas song)|Move]]\"\n|[[The Mamas]]\n|1\n|-\n|20 March\n|\"Svag\"\n|Victor Leksell\n|1\n|-\n|27 March\n|\"Blinding Lights\"\n|The Weeknd\n|2\n|}\n<!--\n== See also ==\n* [[2020 in Swedish music]]-->\n\n== External links ==\n* {{in lang|sv}} [http://www.sverigetopplistan.se/ Sverigetopplistan]\n* [http://swedishcharts.com/index.asp Swedishcharts.com]\n\n{{SwedishNumber1s}}\n\n<!--[[Category:2020s in Swedish music|Number-one singles]]-->\n[[Category:2020s record charts|Sweden]]\n[[Category:Lists of number-one songs in Sweden|2020s]]\n", "name_user": "Ss112", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNumber-one singles", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_number-one_singles_of_the_2020s_(Sweden)"}
{"title_page": "World of Krypton", "text_new": "{{short description|Limited series}}\n{{Infobox comic book title\n<!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics-->\n| image = WorldOfKrypton01-cover.jpg\n| caption = ''World of Krypton'' #1 (July 1979). Artwork by [[Ross Andru]] and [[Dick Giordano]].\n| schedule = Monthly\n| format = standard\n|limited =y\n| publisher = [[DC Comics]]\n| date = July \u2013 September 1979\n| issues = 3\n| main_char_team = [[Jor-El]]\n| writers = [[Paul Kupperberg]]\n| artists = \n| pencillers = [[Howard Chaykin]]\n| inkers = [[Murphy Anderson]], [[Frank Chiaramonte]]\n| colorists = [[Adrienne Roy]], [[Jerry Serpe]]\n| letterers = [[Ben Oda]], [[Shelly Leferman]]\n| editors = [[E. Nelson Bridwell]]\n| creative_team_month = \n| creative_team_year = \n|subcat=DC Comics\n|sort=World of Krypton\n| TPB = Superman: The Many Worlds of Krypton\n| ISBN = 978-1401278892\n}}\n'''''World of Krypton''''' is an American three-issue [[comic book]] [[Limited series (comics)|limited series]] written by [[Paul Kupperberg]] and penciled by [[Howard Chaykin]]. It was the comics industry's first [[Limited series (comics)|miniseries]]. ''World of Krypton'' was published by [[DC Comics]] from July to September 1979.\n\nTaking place in the [[Silver Age of Comic Books|Silver Age]] era of DC Comics history, the series explores [[Superman]]'s home world of [[Krypton (comics)|Krypton]]. The story details his father [[Jor-El]]'s life, the launch of the rocket that carried [[Kal-El]] to Earth, and the destruction of the planet.\n\n==Background and creation==\n\"The Fabulous World of Krypton\" had been a recurring back-up feature in ''[[Superman (comic book)|Superman]]'' and other titles since the early 1970s. The feature was created by [[E. Nelson Bridwell]] and many stories were written by [[Cary Bates]].\n\nThe stories comprising ''World of Krypton'' were originally scheduled to be published in ''[[Showcase (comics)|Showcase]]'' #104-106 to coincide with the premiere of the 1978 film ''[[Superman: The Movie]]''. (Those issues would have had cover-dates of Sept. 1978\u2013Nov. 1978.) When the film's release date was delayed, the stories were rescheduled for ''Showcase'' issues #110-112 (cover dates Apr.\u2013May 1979). In the meantime, however, the ''Showcase'' title was canceled as part of the so-called \"[[DC Implosion]].\"<ref name=\"back71\">{{cite journal |last=Johnson|first=Dan|title=Showcase Presents... Again|journal=[[Back Issue!]]|issue=71|pages=50\u201355|publisher=[[TwoMorrows Publishing]]|date=April 2014|location=Raleigh, North Carolina}}</ref>\n\nAt that point, the storyline was revised and released as ''World of Krypton'' \u2014 comics' first ever limited series.<ref name=McAvennie>{{cite book|last=McAvennie|first= Michael|last2=Dolan|first2=Hannah, ed.|chapter= 1970s|title = DC Comics Year By Year A Visual Chronicle|publisher=[[Dorling Kindersley]] |year=2010 |isbn= 978-0-7566-6742-9 |page= 181 |quote = The worldwide success of ''Superman: The Movie'' motivated [DC] to publish more Superman-related titles. With that, editor E. Nelson Bridwell oversaw a project that evolved into comics' first official limited series - ''World of Krypton''...Featuring out-of-this-world artwork from Howard Chaykin, [Paul] Kupperberg's three-issue limited series explored Superman's homeworld.}}</ref><ref name=Callahan /><ref>McCue, Greg S. with Clive Bloom. ''Dark Knights, the New Comics in Context'' (Pluto Press, 1993), p. 61.</ref><ref>Goulart, Ron. ''Over 50 Years of American Comic Books'' (Mallard Press, 1991), p. 292.</ref>\n\nBridwell commissioned the project.<ref name=McAvennie /> Paul Kupperberg, a regular contributor to ''Showcase'' at the time of the story's conception, wrote the storyline. His brother [[Alan Kupperberg]] did uncredited layouts, upon which Chaykin expanded.<ref name=Callahan>{{cite journal|last = Callahan|first = Tim|title = ''World of Krypton'' Comics' First Miniseries|journal = Back Issue!|issue = 62|pages = 59\u201362|publisher = TwoMorrows Publishing|date = February 2013|location= Raleigh, North Carolina}}</ref>\n\n== Plot ==\n''World of Krypton'' provides a great amount of detail into Krypton's history just before its destruction, along with the life story of [[Jor-El]], the world's leading scientist, and his wife [[Lara Lor-Van]]. Superman himself appears in framing sequences, as do notable Kryptonians such as [[General Zod]], [[Jax-Ur]], [[Faora Hu-Ul]], [[Lar Gand]], and [[Beppo (comics)|Beppo]]; as well as Clark Kent's adoptive parents [[Jonathan and Martha Kent]]. \n\nThe individual issues were titled, \"The Jor-El Story,\" \"This Planet Is Doomed!\", and \"The Last Days of Krypton,\" respectively.\n\n== Reception and legacy ==\n''World of Krypton''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s reception was positive, leading to subsequent similar titles and later more ambitious productions like ''[[Camelot 3000]]'' for the [[direct market]] in 1982.<ref name=McAvennie /><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.newcomicreviews.com/GHM/columns/A+/archives/071103.html|title=GHM Columns : GHM Staff : Steve Higgins A+ Graphic Novels &#93|website=Newcomicreviews.com|access-date=March 5, 2019 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120204110919/http://www.newcomicreviews.com/GHM/columns/A+/archives/071103.html | archive-date=February 4, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n''World of Krypton'' was reprinted and translated on a number of occasions. It was republished, in part or in whole, in ''Superman the Comic'' #2 ([[K.G. Murray Publishing Company]], 1978), ''[[The Best of DC]]'' #5 (May-June 1980), and [[Tor Books]]' ''World of Krypton'' (June 1982). It has been translated into German, French, Swedish, Norwegian, Portuguese, and Italian.\n\nDC published another ''World of Krypton'' miniseries from December 1987 to March 1988. Produced after the [[retcon]] events of ''[[Crisis on Infinite Earths]]'', Krypton itself was the main subject of the latter ''The World of Krypton'' miniseries. Written by [[John Byrne (comics)|John Byrne]] and illustrated by [[Mike Mignola]], it fills in much of Krypton's new history.\n\nIn 2018, DC published the trade paperback ''Superman: The Many Worlds of Krypton'', which collected both ''World of Krypton'' miniseries as well as stories from ''[[Superman (comic book)|Superman]]'' #233, 236, 238, 240, 248, 257, 266, and ''[[Superman Family]]'' #182.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{gcdb series|id=2496|title=''World of Krypton'' (1979)}}\n* [http://www.mikesamazingworld.com/mikes/features/story.php?storyid=27000 ''World of Krypton'' #1 at Mike's Amazing World]\n* [http://www.mikesamazingworld.com/mikes/features/story.php?storyid=27001 ''World of Krypton'' #2 at Mike's Amazing World]\n* [http://www.mikesamazingworld.com/mikes/features/story.php?storyid=27002 ''World of Krypton'' #3 at Mike's Amazing World]\n\n{{Superman}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:World of Krypton}}\n[[Category:1979 comics debuts]]\n[[Category:1979 comics endings]]\n[[Category:Comics by Paul Kupperberg]]\n[[Category:Defunct American comics]]\n[[Category:Superman titles]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Limited series}}\n{{Infobox comic book title\n<!--Wikipedia:WikiProject Comics-->\n| title = World of Krypton\n| image = WorldOfKrypton01-cover.jpg\n| caption = ''World of Krypton'' #1 (July 1979). Artwork by [[Ross Andru]] and [[Dick Giordano]].\n| schedule = Monthly\n| format = standard\n|limited =y\n| publisher = [[DC Comics]]\n| date = July \u2013 September 1979\n| issues = 3\n| main_char_team = [[Jor-El]]\n| writers = [[Paul Kupperberg]]\n| artists = \n| pencillers = [[Howard Chaykin]]\n| inkers = [[Murphy Anderson]], [[Frank Chiaramonte]]\n| colorists = [[Adrienne Roy]], [[Jerry Serpe]]\n| letterers = [[Ben Oda]], [[Shelly Leferman]]\n| editors = [[E. Nelson Bridwell]]\n| creative_team_month = \n| creative_team_year = \n|subcat=DC Comics\n|sort=World of Krypton\n| TPB = Superman: The Many Worlds of Krypton\n| ISBN = 978-1401278892\n}}\n'''''World of Krypton''''' is an American three-issue [[comic book]] [[Limited series (comics)|limited series]] written by [[Paul Kupperberg]] and penciled by [[Howard Chaykin]]. It was the comics industry's first [[Limited series (comics)|miniseries]]. ''World of Krypton'' was published by [[DC Comics]] from July to September 1979.\n\nTaking place in the [[Silver Age of Comic Books|Silver Age]] era of DC Comics history, the series explores [[Superman]]'s home world of [[Krypton (comics)|Krypton]]. The story details his father [[Jor-El]]'s life, the launch of the rocket that carried [[Kal-El]] to Earth, and the destruction of the planet.\n\n==Background and creation==\n\"The Fabulous World of Krypton\" had been a recurring back-up feature in ''[[Superman (comic book)|Superman]]'' and other titles since the early 1970s. The feature was created by [[E. Nelson Bridwell]] and many stories were written by [[Cary Bates]].\n\nThe stories comprising ''World of Krypton'' were originally scheduled to be published in ''[[Showcase (comics)|Showcase]]'' #104-106 to coincide with the premiere of the 1978 film ''[[Superman: The Movie]]''. (Those issues would have had cover-dates of Sept. 1978\u2013Nov. 1978.) When the film's release date was delayed, the stories were rescheduled for ''Showcase'' issues #110-112 (cover dates Apr.\u2013May 1979). In the meantime, however, the ''Showcase'' title was canceled as part of the so-called \"[[DC Implosion]].\"<ref name=\"back71\">{{cite journal |last=Johnson|first=Dan|title=Showcase Presents... Again|journal=[[Back Issue!]]|issue=71|pages=50\u201355|publisher=[[TwoMorrows Publishing]]|date=April 2014|location=Raleigh, North Carolina}}</ref>\n\nAt that point, the storyline was revised and released as ''World of Krypton'' \u2014 comics' first ever limited series.<ref name=McAvennie>{{cite book|last=McAvennie|first= Michael|last2=Dolan|first2=Hannah, ed.|chapter= 1970s|title = DC Comics Year By Year A Visual Chronicle|publisher=[[Dorling Kindersley]] |year=2010 |isbn= 978-0-7566-6742-9 |page= 181 |quote = The worldwide success of ''Superman: The Movie'' motivated [DC] to publish more Superman-related titles. With that, editor E. Nelson Bridwell oversaw a project that evolved into comics' first official limited series - ''World of Krypton''...Featuring out-of-this-world artwork from Howard Chaykin, [Paul] Kupperberg's three-issue limited series explored Superman's homeworld.}}</ref><ref name=Callahan /><ref>McCue, Greg S. with Clive Bloom. ''Dark Knights, the New Comics in Context'' (Pluto Press, 1993), p. 61.</ref><ref>Goulart, Ron. ''Over 50 Years of American Comic Books'' (Mallard Press, 1991), p. 292.</ref>\n\nBridwell commissioned the project.<ref name=McAvennie /> Paul Kupperberg, a regular contributor to ''Showcase'' at the time of the story's conception, wrote the storyline. His brother [[Alan Kupperberg]] did uncredited layouts, upon which Chaykin expanded.<ref name=Callahan>{{cite journal|last = Callahan|first = Tim|title = ''World of Krypton'' Comics' First Miniseries|journal = Back Issue!|issue = 62|pages = 59\u201362|publisher = TwoMorrows Publishing|date = February 2013|location= Raleigh, North Carolina}}</ref>\n\n== Plot ==\n''World of Krypton'' provides a great amount of detail into Krypton's history just before its destruction, along with the life story of [[Jor-El]], the world's leading scientist, and his wife [[Lara Lor-Van]]. Superman himself appears in framing sequences, as do notable Kryptonians such as [[General Zod]], [[Jax-Ur]], [[Faora Hu-Ul]], [[Lar Gand]], and [[Beppo (comics)|Beppo]]; as well as Clark Kent's adoptive parents [[Jonathan and Martha Kent]]. \n\nThe individual issues were titled, \"The Jor-El Story,\" \"This Planet Is Doomed!\", and \"The Last Days of Krypton,\" respectively.\n\n== Reception and legacy ==\n''World of Krypton''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s reception was positive, leading to subsequent similar titles and later more ambitious productions like ''[[Camelot 3000]]'' for the [[direct market]] in 1982.<ref name=McAvennie /><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.newcomicreviews.com/GHM/columns/A+/archives/071103.html|title=GHM Columns : GHM Staff : Steve Higgins A+ Graphic Novels &#93|website=Newcomicreviews.com|access-date=March 5, 2019 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120204110919/http://www.newcomicreviews.com/GHM/columns/A+/archives/071103.html | archive-date=February 4, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n''World of Krypton'' was reprinted and translated on a number of occasions. It was republished, in part or in whole, in ''Superman the Comic'' #2 ([[K.G. Murray Publishing Company]], 1978), ''[[The Best of DC]]'' #5 (May-June 1980), and [[Tor Books]]' ''World of Krypton'' (June 1982). It has been translated into German, French, Swedish, Norwegian, Portuguese, and Italian.\n\nDC published another ''World of Krypton'' miniseries from December 1987 to March 1988. Produced after the [[retcon]] events of ''[[Crisis on Infinite Earths]]'', Krypton itself was the main subject of the latter ''The World of Krypton'' miniseries. Written by [[John Byrne (comics)|John Byrne]] and illustrated by [[Mike Mignola]], it fills in much of Krypton's new history.\n\nIn 2018, DC published the trade paperback ''Superman: The Many Worlds of Krypton'', which collected both ''World of Krypton'' miniseries as well as stories from ''[[Superman (comic book)|Superman]]'' #233, 236, 238, 240, 248, 257, 266, and ''[[Superman Family]]'' #182.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{gcdb series|id=2496|title=''World of Krypton'' (1979)}}\n* [http://www.mikesamazingworld.com/mikes/features/story.php?storyid=27000 ''World of Krypton'' #1 at Mike's Amazing World]\n* [http://www.mikesamazingworld.com/mikes/features/story.php?storyid=27001 ''World of Krypton'' #2 at Mike's Amazing World]\n* [http://www.mikesamazingworld.com/mikes/features/story.php?storyid=27002 ''World of Krypton'' #3 at Mike's Amazing World]\n\n{{Superman}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:World of 